{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_16","type":"agent_message","text":"# WakeTask iPhone Spec Candidate — GPT-5 Codex (Independent)\n\nNote: the referenced artifacts (`.workflow/iphone-app-factory/research-synthesis.md`, `opportunity-matrix.json`, `quality-bar.json`) are not present in this workspace, so this candidate is based on the provided stage outcomes and WakeTask context.\n\n## Problem Statement\nPeople who wake up and immediately lose momentum struggle to convert intent into action. Existing alarm/todo apps either stop at wake-up or task management, but don’t tightly couple “alarm dismissal” with “first meaningful task execution,” leading to snooze loops and unproductive mornings.\n\n## Target User\n- Primary: busy professionals/students (18–40) with recurring morning goals and frequent snoozing/procrastination.\n- Secondary: ADHD-leaning users who benefit from tight, low-friction activation workflows.\n- Exclusions for MVP: enterprise teams, family accounts, wearable-only users.\n\n## MVP Feature Set\n1. `Mission Alarm`\n- User sets wake time + “first task mission.”\n- Alarm dismissal requires completing a short activation sequence tied to the mission.\n\n2. `Wake-to-Task Flow`\n- Post-dismissal full-screen “Now Start” card with a 3-step guided kickoff (stand up, hydrate, first action).\n- 10-minute focus timer starts automatically.\n\n3. `Task Capture + Morning Queue`\n- Lightweight task queue limited to “Today Morning” scope.\n- One-tap reorder/prioritize.\n\n4. `Anti-Snooze Friction Controls`\n- Configurable snooze budget.\n- Escalating friction (longer hold, typed phrase, simple cognitive check) when snoozing repeatedly.\n\n5. `Streaks + Outcome Tracking`\n- Track “alarm dismissed on time,” “mission started within 5 min,” “first focus completed.”\n- Daily/weekly summary.\n\n6. `Notifications`\n- Local notifications only for alarm, reminders, mission nudges.\n\n## Non-Goals (MVP)\n- Social accountability groups.\n- AI voice coach/chatbot.\n- Full project management features.\n- Calendar bi-directional sync.\n- HealthKit or wearable integrations.\n- Cross-platform (iPad, Watch, Android) parity.\n\n## User Journeys\n1. First-Time Setup\n- Install → onboarding (goal selection, wake time, first mission, permission prompts) → test alarm preview.\n\n2. Daily Success Path\n- Alarm rings → user completes dismissal challenge → sees mission card → starts first action within 5 min → completes 10-min focus → streak increments.\n\n3. Snooze Recovery Path\n- User snoozes twice → friction increases → user still dismisses → app presents reduced “minimum viable morning” plan.\n\n4. Missed Morning Path\n- User misses alarm window → app offers “restart morning in 3 minutes” flow to salvage day.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- User can create/edit/delete alarms with associated mission.\n- Alarm cannot be dismissed without completing configured dismissal interaction.\n- After dismissal, mission card appears within 1 second and focus timer can start in one tap.\n- Morning task queue persists across relaunch and device restart.\n- Streak metrics update correctly for success/failure states.\n- Notification permissions degrade gracefully (user still can use app with in-app reminders).\n- No crash in onboarding, alarm flow, snooze flow across last 2 iOS major versions supported by boilerplate.\n- Offline-first behavior works for all MVP features.\n\n## Analytics / Events\n- `onboarding_started`\n- `onboarding_completed`\n- `alarm_created`\n- `alarm_fired`\n- `alarm_snoozed`\n- `alarm_dismissed`\n- `mission_started`\n- `mission_started_within_5m` (bool)\n- `focus_10m_completed`\n- `streak_incremented`\n- `streak_broken`\n- `morning_recovery_started`\n- `notification_permission_granted|denied`\n\nEvent properties:\n- `user_local_time`, `weekday`, `snooze_count`, `dismissal_mode`, `mission_type`, `time_to_mission_start_sec`.\n\n## Privacy & Security Requirements\n- Collect minimum telemetry; no sensitive personal content in analytics payloads.\n- Local data encrypted at rest using platform file protection defaults.\n- No third-party data sale/sharing.\n- Clear consent screen for analytics and notifications.\n- Privacy policy must disclose retention periods and deletion method.\n- Use HTTPS/TLS for any networked analytics.\n- PII fields forbidden in logs/crash breadcrumbs.\n\n## App Store 4.3 Differentiation Statement\nWakeTask is not a generic template alarm/todo clone. Its core differentiator is a purpose-built “wake-to-task activation loop”: alarm dismissal is behaviorally linked to immediate mission start and measured first-focus completion. The product combines anti-snooze friction logic, mission-coupled dismissal, and recovery pathways into a distinct morning-execution workflow, with unique copy, UI system, and feature composition specific to WakeTask.\n\n## Appium Exploratory Testing Requirements\n- Cover onboarding, permission flows, alarm creation/editing, alarm trigger simulation path, snooze escalation, dismissal completion, mission start, streak updates.\n- Run on at least:\n  - iPhone 15 (latest iOS)\n  - iPhone SE class device (small-screen constraints)\n- Include interrupted-state tests:\n  - App background/foreground during alarm\n  - Notification permission denied\n  - Device locked/unlocked transitions\n- Capture screenshots/video for each critical path.\n- Log flaky steps and classify by reproducibility (always/intermittent/rare).\n\n## SwiftAIBoilerplatePro Module Reuse Plan\n- Reuse existing app shell/composition root, routing, design system tokens, and environment config.\n- Reuse auth/user scaffolding only if required for optional cloud sync; otherwise run local-first anonymous mode.\n- Reuse analytics abstraction layer for event instrumentation.\n- Reuse notification and settings modules for alarm/reminder controls.\n- Remove/disable unused template modules (e.g., chat-heavy/demo flows) to reduce binary similarity risk and tighten 4.3 posture.\n- Follow boilerplate’s MVVM/state patterns and dependency injection conventions.\n\n## Definition of Done\n- All MVP acceptance criteria pass.\n- Unit tests for alarm scheduling logic, snooze escalation rules, streak calculations.\n- UI tests for onboarding + core wake-to-task flow.\n- Appium exploratory suite executed with report artifacts.\n- Privacy policy and in-app consent UX implemented.\n- App Store metadata and review notes include differentiation rationale.\n- Unused boilerplate modules removed or fully hidden from nav/build targets.\n- Build passes CI and release configuration is production-ready."}}
